summary.seg: This manuscript, probably copied in the 12th century, or possibly the first two-thirds of the 13th, is a Gospel book illustrated with portrait miniatures of the four Evangelists. The text is fully equipped for liturgical use, with notes identifying the lections to be read in church included as part of the original process of production. The main content is also preceded by listings of the different lection cycles to enable the relevant passage to be found and explanatory notes on aspects of the lection system, and by an excerpt from the 3rd-century chronicle of Hippolytos of Thebes.

The manuscript was probably produced in a region on the fringes of the Greek-speaking world, perhaps in southern Italy, where, Greek communities persisted after the end of Byzantine rule in Sicily in the 10th century and on the mainland in the 11th. The script is quite crude and the parchment is of poor quality, containing numerous holes created during the stretching and drying of the skin. When making a high-grade manuscript, any sheet in which such holes appeared would have been rejected, while even in more humble products of the Byzantine mainstream they were usually only used if the holes were positioned where they could be kept to the margins, rather than impairing the writing surface itself. In peripheral regions such as southern Italy standards were often lower, leading to the appearance of manuscripts such as this one, in which the text is frequently interrupted by holes in the material, appearing right in the midst of the written area. The use of yellow paint in some of its decoration is also common in manuscripts from that region but unusual in those from the Byzantine mainstream at this time.

Three of the portrait miniatures, painted without the use of gold, survive but have suffered severe abrasion. The folio which, judging by its location, presumably bore the fourth, that of St Mark, has been cut out. It may be speculated that when this occurred the other miniatures were already seriously damaged but this one remained relatively intact, enabling it to be sold.

The manuscript was bound in the past, its quires remaining largely stitched together and retaining some cloth used in the construction of the binding, but has now lost its boards and covering, while some of the early quires have become detached. It has also suffered severely from the effects of mould.

support.material: Parchment (FHHF), of medium thickness and poor quality, with many holes dating to the time of production, some within the written surface.

supportDesc.foliation: The manuscript is foliated with the numbers 4-76, 78-180, [181], 182-215, in pencil, in Arabic numerals, recto, upper right. From f. 78r onwards, these have been corrected, increasing each number by one, as a result of an error in the original foliation. Folio numbers 1-3 and 77 have been assigned to leaves no longer present in the volume (as per historic foliation practices at Cambridge University Library).

collation.p: The manuscript consists of 27 quires, all quaternia.

list.item: Quire 18-3 ff. 4-8 The first three folios have been lost, with loss of text.
Quire 58-1 ff. 33-39 The seventh folio has been cancelled, without loss of text.
Quire 108-1 ff. 72-79 The sixth folio has been lost, probably with the loss of a miniature.

collation.signatures: There are modern quire signatures in pencil, in Greek numerals, on the first folio of each quire, recto, lower centre, and on the last folio of each quire, recto, lower right. Probably original to the production of the manuscript. Some have been lost to cropping. They survive on Quires 2-27 (βʹ-κζʹ)

supportDesc.condition: The first three quires (ff. 4-24) are detached. Almost all of f. [181] has been torn away. There have been losses from the edges of ff. 4-11, which have been repaired with Japanese paper. There is purple mould staining through much of the manuscript (ff. 4r-113r), very severe at the beginning and gradually dwindling further into the book-block. This has rendered the first few folios fragile. There is some pest damage to ff. 4-5. All of the surviving miniatures have suffered severe abrasion. Abrasion has also caused significant loss of text on f. 4r, and there has been some fading of text elsewhere. There is water staining and areas of dirt, mild cockling and some creasing.

layoutDesc.layout:
A single column of 24 lines. 160 115
Pricking does not survive. Ruled in hardpoint, system Leroy 1, type Leroy 02C1. Text hangs from the lines, but quite erratically. The ruling is often very faint.

handNote.p: The text was copied by Hand A in upright, blocky mixed minuscule script, in black ink, with minimal variation in letter size.

Syllabic abbreviations and superscript word endings appear only at the end of lines. Breathings are both angular and round, but do not appear in the half-H form, and mute iota is absent. Use of the double dot is functional only. There is accentuation of all lengths of nomina sacra. The double grave accent is in use. Accents are sometimes joined to nomina sacra strokes.
The modern eta and flat-bottomed omega are present.
Punctuation used includes the middle and upper points, lower comma, question mark and full stop.
Headings are written in epigraphic display majuscule script, in red ink.

decoNote.p: Portraits of the Evangelists precede the Gospels of Matthew, Luke and John. A folio has been removed before the beginning of the Gospel of Mark (the former f. 77), which would presumably have borne the miniature of St Mark. The miniatures have suffered from severe abrasion, and parts of their borders have sometimes been lost to cropping.

Each Gospel is preceded by a rectangular headpiece: those for Matthew and Luke follow one style, in red and black ink, while those of Mark and John are in a different style, outlined in black ink with red, yellow blue and green paint infill.

The beginning of the menologion section of the summary lectionary and the chapter lists for Mark and Luke are preceded by slender bands of ornament, outlined in black ink with red paint infill: ff. 8v, 76r, 117r.
The text of each Gospel begins with a relatively small ornamented major initial in the same style as the headpiece.

decoDesc.decoNote: Sections of the text, items of contents lists and lection notes begin with simple minor initials in red ink.
The end of texts is sometimes followed by simple vignettes in black and red ink.

additions.p: As part of the original production of the manuscript, the scribe has included marginal κεφάλαιον (chapter) numbers and titles (τίτλοι), Ammonian section and Eusebian canon numbers, while ἀρχὴ and τέλος marks indicating the beginning and end of lections are included within the body of the text. All this apparatus is in black ink with red initial letters.

There are later annotations in Greek by various hands. These include a note on f. 116v with the date 18 February 1267: Μὴν Φεβρουάριος εἰς τὰς ιηʹ ἁπ[..]ρενος Ἰωάννης ηνέ ἐν ἔτει ͵ϛψοεʹ ἰνδικτιῶνος ιʹ, and another on f. 183v which is largely illegible but gives a date that appears to be 1280: [..14..] ἔτους ͵ϛψπηʹ.
Notes in English, in pencil, have been added regarding lost folios, by Henry Bradshaw (1831-1886) Bradshaw, Henry, 1831-1886 , University Librarian 1867-1886

binding.p: The manuscript is without boards or cover. The quires are partially sewn together, on three stations. A scrap of fabric from a binding survives towards the tail-edge.

accMat.p: The manuscript is accompanied by a note by one W. R. Smith (perhaps the scholar William Robertson Smith (1846-1894) Smith, W. Robertson (William Robertson), 1846-1894 ) regarding the provenance of the manuscript: This MS. lay for a long time in the shop of Mr Orrock, bookbinder North Bridge Edinburgh. He did not know the owner and allowed me to bring it to Cambridge for examination He has of course the right to call it back W R Smith, and by a letter dated 18 October 1895 to Francis Jenkinson (1853-1923) Jenkinson, Francis, 1853-1923 , Librarian of Cambridge University Library from Mr Orrock, agreeing to the price of £6 for the purchase of the manuscript.
Two detached pieces of sewing thread in plastic bags are preserved with the manuscript.

history.origin: The manuscript was probably copied in the 12th or first two-thirds of the 13th century, as suggested by the style of script. A 12th-century date is more likely, as features such as the use of angular breathings are rare after the middle of that century. Hoever, there are also indications that the manuscript was produced in a peripheral region, perhaps southern Italy, as suggested by the poor quality of parchment and the use of yellow paint in some of the ornament. In this case, the script could plausibly display features no longer common in metropolitan production. In any case, it must have been completed before the addition of the dated annotation on f. 116v, in 1267.
history.provenance: Acquired by an Edinburgh bookbinder named Orrock, from a source reportedly unknown to him. The bookbinder Alexander Orrock, Senior Orrock, Alexander was active in Edinburgh at the time of its acquisition; however, the accession register of Additional manuscripts refers to Arch. Orrock, presumably abbreviating the name Archibald, perhaps a relative of Alexander.
history.acquisition: Bought from Orrock by the University Library, 5 November 1895.
